            <h2>The D20</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>In D&amp;D, the d20 is king.</li>
                <li>If you want to do something where your probability of success lies between 1 and<br />99 percent, you will roll a d20.</li>
                <li>This is may be called an ability check, saving throw, or attack (depending on<br />context), but they all function the same way.</li>
                <li>Roll the d20, add your relevant modifiers, and compare the total to the number you<br />have to beat.</li>
                <li>The number you must beat to succeed is called the DC (Difficulty Class) or AC<br />(Armor Class), depending on context.</li>
            </ul>
            <p></p>
            <h2>Modifiers</h2>
            <p>So, now you know how to make a check with a d20. But where do the modifiers come from?<br />They can come from two places, your character stats (abilities) and possibly your proficiency<br />bonus.</p>
            <p></p>
            <h2>Abilities</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>In D&amp;D, abilities are your main stats.</li>
                <li>There are six abilities: Strength, Dexterity, Constitution, Intelligence, Wisdom, and<br />Charisma.</li>
                <li>CONFUSING: Your ability score is NOT the same as your ability modifier. In most<br />cases, the ability modifier is the important number because this is what you will<br />add (or subtract) from a d20 check.</li>
                <li>Fine print example: 10 is the base ability score in D&amp;D. If your Strength is 10, your Strength modifier is<br />0. The modifier then goes up or down by one for every two score. Strength 12 gives you a +1 modifier;<br />Strength 14, a +2; etc.</li>
            </ul>
            <p></p>
